In this part we&rsquo;ll cover all calculation methods that we&rsquo;ll use for AC-circuits. Equivalent Impedance Given the circuit and that $\omega = 5 \dfrac{rad}{s}$ - find the equivalent output impedance: As we discussed in the last part, our resistor rules, for series and parallel apply for impedance as well. Let&rsquo;s first quickly convert the capacitor and inductor to Ohm. For our capacitor: $$  egin{align*} Z_{C} &amp; = \dfrac{1}{j\omega C} 
ewline &amp; = -j \cdot\ \dfrac{1}{\omega C} 
ewline &amp; = -j \cdot\ \dfrac{1}{5 \cdot\ 500 \cdot\ 10^{-3}}\ [\Omega] 
ewline &amp; = -j 0.

In this part we&rsquo;ll work in electrical fields, the connection between electrical fields and voltages as well as how we can use electrical fields with capacitors. Work We&rsquo;ve briefly went over work before in this series - but let&rsquo;s consider the work required to move charges apart from eachother. For example: $$ W = F \cdot\ d\mathbf{\vec{r}} 
ewline $$ $$ \mathbf{\vec{F_{12}}} = k_{e}\ \dfrac{q_1 q_2}{r^2} \mathbf{\vec{r_{12}}} $$ $$  egin{align*} W &amp; = \int_{R}^{\infty} \mathbf{\vec{F}} \cdot\ d\mathbf{\vec{r}} 
ewline &amp; = -k_e q_1 q_2 \int_{R}^{\infty} \dfrac{d\mathbf{\vec{r}}}{r^2} 
ewline &amp; = k_e q_1 q_2 \cdot\ \dfrac{-1}{r} \Big|_R^{\infty} 
ewline &amp; =  oxed{\dfrac{k_e q_1 q_2}{R}} \end{align*} $$

Introduction What do we mean by an &lsquo;Algorithmic complexity&rsquo;, a good (but not fully formal) definition would be - &ldquo;How much resources does the algorithm use in relation to quantitative properties of its input&rdquo;
And just to be clear, the definition of an algorithm: any well-defined procedure to solve a given problem.
So what kind of resources could we quantify from an input? Of course the runtime of an algorithm is important.
